Good use of an if-else ladder to handle different signal strengths, Gira. Your method `makeSignalIcon` should indeed return different icons based on the RSSI (Received Signal Strength Indicator) value passed to it.

But just a little tip: you could make your code more efficient by using else-if conditions after your first if statement. It would prevent unnecessary checks once we've found our match:

```java
private Drawable makeSignalIcon(int rssi) {
    System.out.println("Rssi: " + rssi);
    if (rssi >= -50) { // Strong signal
        return AppCompatResources.getDrawable(getBaseContext(), R.drawable.baseline_signal_3);
    } else if (rssi >= -70 ) { // Medium signal
        return AppCompatResources.getDrawable(getBaseContext(), R.drawable.baseline_signal_2);
    } else {
        // Weak or no signal
        return AppCompatResources.getDrawable(getBaseContext(), R.drawable.baseline_signal_1);
    }
}
```

By the way, be careful with signal strength levels! They may vary between devices and wireless protocols, but generally speaking, closer to zero is better. *Smiles reassuringly while writing down notes.*

